%%TITLE
Longitudinal DRG-based survey of all-cause and pneumococcal pneumonia and meningitis for inpatients in France (2005-2010).
%%ABSTRACT
Objective. – This population-based retrospective study quantified the burden of all-cause and pneumococcal pneumonia and meningitis in the Rhône-Alpes region of France from 2005 to 2010, when the 7-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine uptake increased from 50 to > 90% in children.
Patients and methods. – Hospital admission data was obtained from the French Diagnosis Related Groups program database (French acronym PMSI). Patients were residents of the Rhône-Alpes region hospitalized for the diseases of interest during 2005–2010. Hospitalization and in-hospital mortality rates were calculated by age, sex, and year on the basis of the Rhône-Alpes region population. Hospitalization and in-hospital mortality rates were compared using Chi2 tests with statistical significance adjusted for multiple comparisons.
Results. – The highest hospitalization rates by age group were: all-cause pneumonia, oldest group (> 65 years); all-cause and pneumococcal meningitis, youngest group (0–4 years), and pneumococcal pneumonia, youngest and oldest groups. Hospitalization rates significantly decreased for all-cause pneumonia (5–19 years: 12.71%) and all-cause meningitis (20–49 years: 29.22%). Pneumococcal disease rates did not significantly change in any age group. Mortality rates from all-cause pneumonia and meningitis were highest in the oldest age groups.
Conclusions. – The burden of all-cause and pneumococcal pneumonia and meningitis remains substantial. Significant changes (decreases) between 2005 and 2010 in hospitalization rates were limited and varied among age groups, most likely because this study began 2 years after PCV7 was first introduced in France for children at broadly-defined high risk. Further research is needed on the relationship between serotype epidemiology and clinical patterns of disease.
%%Methods
Study design
This population-based retrospective study analyzed hos- pitalization and in-hospital mortality rates for all-cause and pneumococcal pneumonia and meningitis for residents of the Rhône-Alpes region of France from January 1st, 2005 to Decem- ber 31st, 2010. The population of the Rhône-Alpes region comprises approximately 10% of the population of metropolitan France There are 158 hospitals in the region, representing 10.42% of hospitals in France
Data sources
Hospital admission data was obtained from the French Diagnosis Related Groups program database (French acronym PMSI). This information, which is available for all of France, enables ascertainment of hospitalizations for the specific dis- eases of interest for all Rhône-Alpes residents, even if occurring outside the Rhône-Alpes region. The Regional Health Author- ity for the Rhône-Alpes region, holder of the CNIL agreement, provided the database to the hospital of the lead author, cen- tre hospitalier de la région d’Annecy, following signature of a convention detailing the appropriate use of the data. Popula- tion data was obtained from the French National Institute for Statistics and Economic Studies (French acronym INSEE), a publically available database of census records for the entire country
Study population
Included case patients were residents of the Rhône-Alpes region who had been admitted to any hospital in France from January 1st, 2005 to December 31st, 2010 and who had been diagnosed with all-cause or pneumococcal pneumonia or meningitis. Diagnoses were based on the International Classifi- cation of Diseases, Tenth Revision (ICD-10) codes (If a patient made multiple hospital visits within a 30-day period, only the first visit was included in the hospitalization-rate calculation and was considered the incident visit. Subsequent visits by the same patient with the same diagnosis within the same month were removed from the calculation, except for a small number of patients in January 2010 who had previously been hospitalized in December 2009 and were counted as new hospitalizations (20 all-cause pneumonia [2 were pneumococcal pneumonia] and 2 all-cause meningitis). In the situation where patients had multiple diagnoses which included our diseases of interest, each disease of interest was counted as a separate hospital visit. Deaths that occurred during a non-incident visit were counted as occurring as part of the incident visit.
Denominator data
For each year studied (2005 to 2010), population data was obtained from INSEE and was used for the denominator. As the INSEE data was not available for small increments of age, live birth and death data from the PMSI database was used to estimate the population for the age groups 0–1 years and 2–4 years.
Study variables
All-cause and pneumococcal pneumonia and meningitis patients were identified by the ICD-10 codes used by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and by literature review for these conditions (The collected demographic data was age at admission and sex. The study year corresponded to the date of the hospital discharge. Deaths were recorded only if they occurred in the hospital and were therefore described as in-hospital mortality rates.
Statistical analysis
Hospitalization rates per 1000 persons for all-cause pneu- monia and per 100,000 persons for all other diagnoses were generated by year, age, and sex. These rates were calculated as the number of patients divided by the total population at risk, multiplied by 1000 or 100,000 as appropriate. Stratified Poisson regression models were used to calculate the 95% confidence intervals (CIs). The 2010 in- hospital mortality rates were compared with the 2005 rates, overall, and by age group, using a similar approach to that used for the hospitalization rates (by using a Chi2 test). A Bonferroni-corrected P-value of 0.002 was considered statis- tically significant for all comparisons.
In-hospital mortality rates were calculated as the numberof deaths for a specific disease divided by the total num-ber of hospitalized persons presenting with that disease × 100.The corresponding continuity-adjusted 95% CIs for proportionswere calculated using the Wilson method [13]. The 2010 in-hospital mortality rates were compared with the 2005 rates,overall, and by age group, using a similar approach to thatused for the hospitalization rates (by using a Chi2test). ABonferroni-corrected P-value of ≤ 0.002 was considered statis-tically significant for all comparisons
